A group of civil society organisations wants the Judicial Service Commission (JSC) to stop subjecting candidates to embarrassing questions in the ongoing interviews for the positions of Chief Justice, deputy Chief Justice and Supreme Court judge. The Katiba Institute, International Commission of Jurists and Kenyans for Peace with Truth and Justice said the JSC has breached the Constitution on the minimal requirements for candidates.They said the panellists are interviewing candidates in an arbitrary manner, contrary to the Constitution.They also pointed out that some candidates were being asked superficial questions and giving answers that do not exactly outline how they intend to handle certain issues, such as interpretation of the law and corruption cases.Further, they said subjecting candidates to mundane and irrelevant questions like "Who is the MCA for a certain ward?", is only meant to embarrass them. email print email print Ms Tutui said the court would have given orders for immediate realisation of the rule. But the passport was not stamped, meaning he did not pass through the immigration desk.